english:
  title: The Boatman's Wisdom
  author: Gwon Geun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    A visitor once questioned the Boatman, saying: "You dwell upon your boat, yet you seem to fish without hook, to trade without cargo, to serve as a ferryman without crossing. You float a single leaf upon unfathomable depths, venture across ten thousand leagues of boundless waters. When wind rages wild and waves crash terrifying, when masts crack and oars splinter, when your very soul trembles and life hangs by a thread—you embrace this peril, wander endlessly, and never return. What philosophy sustains you in this?"

    The Boatman sighed deeply and replied: "Ah, have you not considered this? The human heart knows no constancy—it grasps and releases without measure. Upon level ground, we grow complacent and reckless; in dangerous straits, we tremble and shrink. Yet this trembling keeps us vigilant and steadfast, while complacency leads inevitably to dissolution and ruin. I choose rather to dwell in danger with constant awareness than to rest in ease and squander myself.

    Moreover, my boat floats without fixed form. Should it lean to one side, it must surely tip. Only by maintaining equilibrium—neither tilting left nor right, neither heavy nor light—do I preserve its balance. What storm could disturb the peace I have cultivated within?

    Consider: the world of men is but a vast deluge, and the human heart a great tempest. My fragile form drifts within it like a single leaf upon infinite waters. In my years upon this boat, I have witnessed one generation after another—men who trust in their security without heeding danger, who indulge their desires without imagining their end. Many have drowned and capsized. Why do you not fear this fate, yet call my path perilous?"

    Then the Boatman struck his gunwale and sang:

    *Vast the rivers and seas, flowing on without end,
    I float my empty boat mid-current's gentle bend.
    Bearing moonlight alone through the darkness I roam,
    While years drift peacefully, drifting toward home.*

    With that, he bade farewell and departed, speaking no more.
  footnotes:
    - The 'Boatman' represents the Daoist sage who has transcended worldly attachments and found freedom through acceptance of life's fundamental uncertainty.
    - The boat serves as a metaphor for the self navigating the turbulent waters of human society and the inevitable changes of fortune.
    - The concept of maintaining 'equilibrium' (平衡) reflects both nautical balance and the Buddhist-Daoist principle of finding harmony amid chaos.
